        'Even experienced builders encounter conversion errors, especially when working with unfamiliar components or complex schematics. The three most common mistakes are misreading power and ground rail assignments, reversing the orientation of polarity-sensitive components, and leaving connections floating — where a net that should be continuous has a physical gap on the breadboard. Each mistake has distinct symptoms: shorts and overheating suggest power rail confusion, non-functional but undamaged components suggest reversed orientation, and intermittent or absent output suggests floating connections.',
